---
title: "Why Most Operations Dashboards Measure Outputs Instead of Leading Indicators"
date: "2024-04-30"
summary: "Operations dashboards measure outputs. Leading indicators predict outputs. Shift your metrics and see problems before they arrive."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Analytics"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your dashboard shows resolution time. It is 4.2 hours. That is an output. It tells you what happened. It does not tell you what will happen.

Leading indicators are metrics that predict outputs. They move before the output moves. They give you time to act.

Here are the leading indicators that matter.

Queue depth. The number of items waiting. If queue depth is increasing, resolution time will increase. You have days to act before the output degrades.

First response time. The time to first reply. If first response time is increasing, customer satisfaction will decrease. You have hours to act.

Agent utilization. The percentage of capacity being used. If utilization is above 85 percent, errors will increase. You have days to act.

I shifted a client's dashboard from outputs to leading indicators in 2024. The old dashboard showed resolution time and satisfaction. The new one showed queue depth, first response time, and agent utilization. The team could see problems coming days before they appeared in the output metrics.

The response time to problems dropped from reactive to proactive. The output metrics improved as a side effect.

The teams that measure outputs are the ones that react. The teams that measure leading indicators are the ones that prevent.

Measure queue depth. Measure first response time. Measure utilization. The outputs follow.
